            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-RYZ5/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-RYZ5</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-RYZ5/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Chevalley's theorem">Chevalley's theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \to  E]]></fr:tex> is finitely presented. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/topl-XT5Y/" title="Maps preserving constructible sets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-XT5Y/" display-uri="topl-XT5Y" type="local">preserves constructible sets</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> will be of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D[x_1,\cdots ,x_n]/\langle p_i,q_i\rangle ]]></fr:tex>. We may factor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \to  E]]></fr:tex> as
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ D \to  D[x_1] \to  \cdots  \to  D[x_1,\cdots ,x_n] \to  D[x_1,\cdots ,x_n]/\langle p_i,q_i\rangle , ]]></fr:tex>
  where each map preserves constructible sets by <fr:link href="/idem-comm-21XO/" title="Polynomial projections are open, closed, and constructible" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-21XO/" display-uri="idem-comm-21XO" type="local">Lemma <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-21XO/" display-uri="idem-comm-21XO" /></fr:link> and <fr:link href="/idem-comm-Y25U/" title="Finitely presented quotients preserve constructible sets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-Y25U/" display-uri="idem-comm-Y25U" type="local">Lemma <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-Y25U/" display-uri="idem-comm-Y25U" /></fr:link>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>8</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-Y25U/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-Y25U</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-Y25U/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Finitely presented quotients preserve constructible sets">Finitely presented quotients preserve constructible sets</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For a finite lists of elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_i,b_i]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, the inclusion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/\langle a_i,b_i\rangle  \rightarrowtail  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/topl-XT5Y/" title="Maps preserving constructible sets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-XT5Y/" display-uri="topl-XT5Y" type="local">preserves constructible sets</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  This is because the quotient <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \twoheadrightarrow  D/\langle a_i,b_i\rangle ]]></fr:tex> is surjective, hence any constructible set in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D/\langle a_i,b_i\rangle ]]></fr:tex> is the intersection of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/\langle a_i,b_i\rangle ]]></fr:tex> with a constructible set in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>. However, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/\langle a_i,b_i\rangle ]]></fr:tex> is itself constructible by <fr:link href="/idem-comm-80H1/" title="Finitely presented quotient induce constructible subsets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-80H1/" display-uri="idem-comm-80H1" type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-80H1/" display-uri="idem-comm-80H1" /></fr:link>, it follows that the intersection is constructible in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>6</fr:month>
              <fr:day>8</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-21XO/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>idem-comm-21XO</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/idem-comm-21XO/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Polynomial projections are open, closed, and constructible">Polynomial projections are open, closed, and constructible</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  The map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D[x] \to  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> takes a standard open to a standard open; similarly for standard closed sets. This in particular implies it is both open and closed, and <fr:link href="/topl-XT5Y/" title="Maps preserving constructible sets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-XT5Y/" display-uri="topl-XT5Y" type="local">preserves constructible subsets</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  A point in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D[x]]]></fr:tex> can be identified as a pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(i,x)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \in  \{0,1\}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>. This way, given any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> and polynomial <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\in  D[x]]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p = p_0 \vee  x \wedge  p_1]]></fr:tex>, we have
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \in  \operatorname {img}(O_p) \Leftrightarrow  (i,x) \in  O_p \Leftrightarrow  x\in  O_{p_i}. ]]></fr:tex>
  In particular, this means that 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {img}(O_p) = O_{p_0} \cup  O_{p_1} = O_{p_1}. ]]></fr:tex>
  Completely similarly, we have 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {img}(C_p) = C_{p_0} \cup  C_{p_1} = C_{p_0}. ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
